# Valid or invalid

In section, we focus on distinguishing valid from invalid arguments via a discussion of a series of examples.

<br>

*Example 1*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 p/\q :|-: q
~~~

Hence, is the argument with premise $p/\q$ and conclusion $q$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~


*Example 2*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~e\/f :|-: ~e
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $\neg e$ and premise $\neg e\vee f$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~


*Example 3*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~j,~z :|-: ~(j\/z)
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $\neg (j\vee z)$ and premises $\neg j$ and $\neg z$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~

One way to quickly assess this is to see it as a valid argument obtained from an equivalence. Which equivalence can this be seen as an instance of?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| law of double negation
| associativity
| *DeMorgan
| distributivity
~~~


*Example 4*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 q :|-: p\/q
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $p\/q$ and premises $p$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~

*Example 5*

Consider how large the table would be to assess the validity of the following:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $r,t\vdash s\vee (r\wedge t)$ </p>

It turns out that this is a valid argument. What substitution should you do to see this, on the basis of Example 4?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| substitute $s$ for $p$ and substitute $r\wedge t$ for $q$.
| substitute $t$ for $p$ and substitute $r\wedge s$ for $q$.
| *substitute $r\wedge t$ for $q$ and substitute $s$ for $p$.
| substitute $r\wedge s$ for $q$ and substitute $t$ for $p$.
~~~

*Example 6*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 t\/s :|-: (t\/s)/\r
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $(t\/s)/\r$ and premise $t\/s$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~

*Example 7*

Use the table to assess the validity of the argument:

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~a, ~a->b :|-: b
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $b$ and premises $~a$ and $~a\rightarrow b$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~

Which of the following is this example a substitution instance of:

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *modus ponens
| modus tollens
| affirming the consequent
| denying the antecedent
~~~


