*Example 12*

Here is another way to think about the validity from the previous example:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $p\rightarrow q, q\rightarrow r :|-: p\rightarrow r </p>

What is the one circumstance in which the conclusion $p\rightarrow r$ is false?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| when $p$ is true and $r$ is true
| *when $p$ is true and $r$ is false
| when $p$ is false and $r$ is true
| when $p$ is false and $r$ is false
~~~

Given this, if $q$ is true then  premise $q\rightarrow r$ is false; and if $q$ is false then $p\rightarrow q$ is false. Hence, in either case, one of the two premises is false. Hence, in the one circumstance in which the conclusion $p\rightarrow r$ is false, at least one of the premises is false.

The argument we just gave in the previous paragraph is an example of one of the valid arguments we saw in lecture. Which is it?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| disjunctive syllogism
| modus ponens
| *reasoning by cases
| modus tollens
~~~


